Basic Transformer Encoder-Decoder Model¶

Initially, the TransformerEncoderDecoderModel class is defined as a sub-class of keras.Model. The first diagram (Figure 4.3) is a simple architecture of this model, where the model holds 2 encoders and 2 decoders. The second diagram (Figure 4.4), which is made of the same class, represents that the 2 encoders and the 2 decoders have the residual connections.

The other advantage of using the subclassing API of TensorFlow is the capability to save the vocabulary data together into a model file easily, aside from the dynamic customization of the model architecture and the training loop. The vocabulary data, which is held in the 2 TextVectorization layers, is saved in the table of the actual words and their internal IDs with trained parameters in this implementation.

In [ ]:
@saving.register_keras_serializable()
class TransformerEncoderDecoderModel(keras.Model):
    """
    Transformer model class that contains Transformer Encoder and Decoder inside.
    :param encoder_tokenizer: tf.keras.layers.TextVectorization object
    :param decoder_tokenizer: tf.keras.layers.TextVectorization object
    :num_encoders: the number of encoders
    :num_decoders: the number of decoders
    :num_heads: the number of heads (Attention mechanism)
    :dropout: the dropout rate
    :transformer_intermediate_dim: the number of dimensions in each encoder and decoder
    :normalize_first: Pre-Layer Normalization or Post-Layer Normalization
    :layer_norm_epsilon: the epsilon value in layer normalization components.
    :encoder_vocabulary_size: the number of encoder vocabulary size
    :decoder_vocabulary_size: the number of decoder vocabulary size
    :embedding_dim: the dimension for embedding
    :mask_zero: whether 0 is used the mask value
    :encoder_sequence_length: the length of encoder sequence
    :decoder_sequence_length: the length of decoder sequence
    :use_residual: whether residual connections are used outside of the Transformer encoder and decoder
    """
    def __init__(
        self,
        encoder_tokenizer,
        decoder_tokenizer,
        num_encoders,
        num_decoders,
        num_heads,
        dropout,
        transformer_intermediate_dim,
        normalize_first,
        layer_norm_epsilon,
        encoder_vocabulary_size,
        decoder_vocabulary_size,
        embedding_dim,
        mask_zero,
        encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_residual,
        **kwargs):
        super(TransformerEncoderDecoderModel, self).__init__(**kwargs)
        self.mask_zero = mask_zero
        self.layer_norm_epsilon = layer_norm_epsilon
        self.use_residual = use_residual
        self.encoders = []
        self.decoders = []
        if isinstance(layer_norm_epsilon, list):
            encoder_layer_norm_epsilons = layer_norm_epsilon
            decoder_layer_norm_epsilons = layer_norm_epsilon
        else:
            encoder_layer_norm_epsilons = [layer_norm_epsilon for _ in range(num_encoders)]
            decoder_layer_norm_epsilons = [layer_norm_epsilon for _ in range(num_decoders)]

        for i in range(num_encoders):
            self.encoders.append(
                keras_nlp.layers.TransformerEncoder(
                    num_heads=num_heads,
                    dropout=dropout,
                    intermediate_dim=transformer_intermediate_dim,
                    normalize_first=normalize_first,
                    layer_norm_epsilon=encoder_layer_norm_epsilons[i],
                    name=f"encoder_{i}",
                )
            )
        for i in range(num_decoders):
            self.decoders.append(
                keras_nlp.layers.TransformerDecoder(
                    num_heads=num_heads,
                    dropout=dropout,
                    intermediate_dim=transformer_intermediate_dim,
                    normalize_first=normalize_first,
                    layer_norm_epsilon=decoder_layer_norm_epsilons[i],
                    name=f"decoder_{i}",
                )
            )

        self.encoder_tokenizer = encoder_tokenizer
        self.decoder_tokenizer = decoder_tokenizer

        self.encoder_embedding = keras_nlp.layers.TokenAndPositionEmbedding(
            vocabulary_size=encoder_vocabulary_size,
            sequence_length=encoder_sequence_length,
            embedding_dim=embedding_dim,
            mask_zero=mask_zero,
            name="encoder_embed",
        )

        self.decoder_embedding = keras_nlp.layers.TokenAndPositionEmbedding(
            vocabulary_size=decoder_vocabulary_size,
            sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
            embedding_dim=embedding_dim,
            mask_zero=mask_zero,
            name="decoder_embed",
        )

        self.dense = keras.layers.Dense(
            decoder_vocabulary_size,
            name="dense",
        )

    def build(self, input_shape):
        """
        This method must set the shapes of tensors into every layer.
        @see https://github.com/keras-team/keras/issues/19535#issuecomment-2060299275
        fcollet has answered and explained how to implement for the following warning.

        ```
        UserWarning: `build()` was called on layer 'transformer_encoder_decoder_model_*',
        however the layer does not have a `build()` method implemented and it looks like it has unbuilt state.
        This will cause the layer to be marked as built, despite not being actually built, which may cause failures down the line.
        Make sure to implement a proper `build()` method
        ```

        The incorrect implementation of this method causes the following problem:
        - When the model is generated from .keras file, the loaded model does not work correctly.
        """
        self.encoder_embedding.build(input_shape[0])
        self.decoder_embedding.build(input_shape[1])
        encoder_output_shape = self.encoder_embedding.compute_output_shape(input_shape[0])
        decoder_output_shape = self.decoder_embedding.compute_output_shape(input_shape[1])

        for encoder in self.encoders:
            encoder.build(inputs_shape=encoder_output_shape)
            encoder_output_shape = encoder.compute_output_shape(
                inputs_shape=encoder_output_shape
            )
        for decoder in self.decoders:
            decoder.build(
                decoder_sequence_shape=decoder_output_shape,
                encoder_sequence_shape=encoder_output_shape,
            )
            decoder_output_shape = decoder.compute_output_shape(
                decoder_sequence_shape=decoder_output_shape,
            )

        self.dense.build(input_shape=decoder_output_shape)
        self.built = True

    def call(self, inputs, training=False):
        """
        This method defines and represents the calculation graph (tensor flow).
        :training: True, when calculating val_loss and val_acc. Otherwise, False.
        """
        encoder_input, decoder_input = (
            inputs[0],
            inputs[1],
        )
        encoded = self.encoder_embedding(encoder_input)
        for encoder in self.encoders:
            if self.use_residual and len(self.encoders) > 1:
                residual = encoded
            encoded = encoder(
                inputs=encoded,
                training=training,
            )
            if self.use_residual and len(self.encoders) > 1:
                encoded = encoded + residual

        decoded = self.decoder_embedding(decoder_input)
        for decoder in self.decoders:
            if self.use_residual and len(self.decoders) > 1:
                residual = decoded
            decoded = decoder(
                decoder_sequence=decoded,
                encoder_sequence=encoded,
                use_causal_mask=True,
                training=training,
            )
            if self.use_residual and len(self.decoders) > 1:
                decoded = decoded + residual

        output = self.dense(decoded)

        try:
            # Drop the keras mask, so it doesn't scale the losses/metrics.
            # b/250038731
            del output._keras_mask
        except AttributeError:
            pass
        return output

    def get_config(self):
        """
        This method is used to save a model into a file.
        """
        config = super(TransformerEncoderDecoderModel, self).get_config().copy()
        config.update({
            "encoder_tokenizer": self.encoder_tokenizer.get_config(),
            "decoder_tokenizer": self.decoder_tokenizer.get_config(),
            "num_encoders": len(self.encoders),
            "num_decoders": len(self.decoders),
            "num_heads": self.encoders[0].num_heads,
            "dropout" : self.encoders[0].dropout,
            "transformer_intermediate_dim": self.encoders[0].intermediate_dim,
            "normalize_first": self.encoders[0].normalize_first,
            "layer_norm_epsilon": self.layer_norm_epsilon,
            "encoder_vocabulary_size": self.encoder_embedding.vocabulary_size,
            "decoder_vocabulary_size": self.decoder_embedding.vocabulary_size,
            "embedding_dim": self.encoder_embedding.embedding_dim,
            "mask_zero": self.mask_zero,
            "encoder_sequence_length": self.encoder_embedding.sequence_length,
            "decoder_sequence_length": self.decoder_embedding.sequence_length,
            "use_residual": self.use_residual,
        })
        return config
    @classmethod
    def from_config(cls, config):
        """
        This method is used to build a model from a saved file.
        """
        encoder_tokenizer_config = config.pop("encoder_tokenizer")
        decoder_tokenizer_config = config.pop("decoder_tokenizer")
        encoder_tokenizer = keras.layers.TextVectorization.from_config(encoder_tokenizer_config)
        decoder_tokenizer = keras.layers.TextVectorization.from_config(decoder_tokenizer_config)
        return cls(
            encoder_tokenizer=encoder_tokenizer,
            decoder_tokenizer=decoder_tokenizer,
            **config
        )

Prediction¶

Firstly, the text that is summarized and the start OOV token "[start]" are given into the encoder input and the decoder input, respectively. Then, the first word that follows "[start]" is derived from the decoder output. Next, the outputted word is combined with the previous input sequence, and it is used as the next input sequence of the decoder input. At this time, the encoder input is not changed. This process is repeatedly executed until the decoder output contains the end OOV token "[end]" or reaches the maximum length. Finally, the summarized text is completed.

Unlike the classification task, it computationally takes O(n) in proportion to the length of the summarized text. That might be one of the disadvantages if the task summarizes much longer text.

In [ ]:
import nltk
nltk.download('punkt')
nltk.download('averaged_perceptron_tagger')

def post_process(text):
    text = text.replace("[start] ", "")
    text = text.replace(" [end]", "")
    sentences = nltk.sent_tokenize(text)
    ss = []
    for sentence in sentences:
        sentence = sentence.capitalize()
        tokens = nltk.tokenize.word_tokenize(text=sentence)
        tagged_tokens = nltk.tag.pos_tag(tokens=tokens)
        result = []
        for i, (token, tag) in enumerate(tagged_tokens):
            if i == 0:  # The first word of the sentence
                result.append(token.capitalize())
            elif tag.startswith('NNP'):  # proper noun
                result.append(token.capitalize())
            else:
                result.append(token.lower())
        s = " ".join(result)
        ss.append(s)
    text = " ".join(ss)
    text = text.replace(" ,", ",")
    text = text.replace(" .", ".")
    # Revert OOV.
    # text = '[start] ' + text + ' [end]'
    return text

def decode_sequence(
        input_sentence,
        model,
        max_sequence_length,
        lookup_table,
        use_post_processing=False):
    """
    Generate summarized text from the input sentence.
    :input_sentence: the original text that is summarized
    :model: the TransformerEncoderDecoderModel class model
    :max_sequence_length: the maximum length of the summarized text
    :lookup_table: the table holds token IDs and their actual words
    """
    encoder_tokenizer = model.encoder_tokenizer
    decoder_tokenizer = model.decoder_tokenizer
    tokenized_input = encoder_tokenizer([input_sentence])

    start_token = decoder_tokenizer("[start]")[0].numpy()
    end_token = decoder_tokenizer("[end]")[0].numpy()

    decoded_sentence = [start_token]
    for i in range(max_sequence_length):
        decoder_inputs = tf.convert_to_tensor(
            [decoded_sentence],
            dtype="int64",
        )
        decoder_inputs = tf.concat(
            [
                decoder_inputs,
                tf.zeros(
                    [1, max_sequence_length - i - 1],
                    dtype="int64",
                ),
            ],
            axis=1,
        )
        input = (
            tokenized_input,
            decoder_inputs,
        )
        predictions = model(input)
        predicted_token = np.argmax(predictions[0, i, :])
        decoded_sentence.append(predicted_token)
        if predicted_token == end_token:
            break

    detokenized_output = []
    for token in decoded_sentence:
        detokenized_output.append(lookup_table[token])
    text = " ".join(detokenized_output)
    if use_post_processing:
        text = post_process(text=text)
    return text


def predict_main(
        filepath,
        examples,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_post_processing=False):
    """
    Generate summarized text with the model file.
    :filepath: the file path specifies the model
    :examples: the list of text that is summarized.
    :decoder_sequence_length: the maximum length of the summarized text.
    """
    loaded_model = keras.models.load_model(
        filepath,
        # Just in case, TransformerEncoderDecoderModel is specified.
        # However, it does not seem necessary.
        custom_objects={
            "TransformerEncoderDecoderModel": TransformerEncoderDecoderModel,
            "Seq2SeqModel": Seq2SeqModel,
        }
    )

    decoder_tokenizer = loaded_model.decoder_tokenizer
    vocab = decoder_tokenizer.get_vocabulary()
    index_lookup_table = dict(zip(range(len(vocab)), vocab))

    summarized = []
    for example in examples:
        summarized.append(
            decode_sequence(
                example,
                loaded_model,
                decoder_sequence_length,
                index_lookup_table,
                use_post_processing=use_post_processing,
            )
        )

    for i in range(len(examples)):
        print("ORIGINAL SENTENCE: ", examples[i])
        print("SUMMARIZED RESULT: ", summarized[i])

def predict_model(
        model,
        examples,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_post_processing=False):
    """
    Generate summarized text with the model.
    :model: the file path specifies the model
    :examples: the list of text that is summarized.
    :decoder_sequence_length: the maximum length of the summarized text.
    """
    decoder_tokenizer = model.decoder_tokenizer
    vocab = decoder_tokenizer.get_vocabulary()
    index_lookup_table = dict(zip(range(len(vocab)), vocab))

    summarized = []
    for example in examples:
        summarized.append(
            decode_sequence(
                example,
                model,
                decoder_sequence_length,
                index_lookup_table,
                use_post_processing=use_post_processing,
            )
        )

    for i in range(len(examples)):
        print("ORIGINAL SENTENCE: ", examples[i])
        print("SUMMARIZED RESULT: ", summarized[i])

def predict_dataset(
        model,
        iterable_dataset,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_post_processing=False):
    """
    Generate summarized text with the model.
    :model: the file path specifies the model
    :iterable_dataset: the dataset, which is mainly test set, used to generate summarized text.
    :decoder_sequence_length: the maximum length of the summarized text.
    """
    decoder_tokenizer = model.decoder_tokenizer
    vocab = decoder_tokenizer.get_vocabulary()
    index_lookup_table = dict(zip(range(len(vocab)), vocab))

    y_trues = []
    y_preds = []
    for entry in iterable_dataset:
        text = entry["dialogue"]
        result = decode_sequence(
            text,
            model,
            decoder_sequence_length,
            index_lookup_table,
            use_post_processing=use_post_processing,
        )
        y_true = entry["summary"]
        y_true = y_true.decode('utf-8')
        y_pred = result.replace('[start]', '').replace('[end]', '').strip()
        # print(y_true, '\n\t' , y_pred)
        y_trues.append(y_true)
        y_preds.append(y_pred)
    return y_trues, y_preds

def calculate_rouge_score(y_true, y_pred):
    """
    # RougeN metric
    # @see https://keras.io/api/keras_nlp/metrics/rouge_n/
    """
    rouge_n = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeN(order=2)
    rouge_2_score = rouge_n(y_true, y_pred)
    rouge_n = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeN(order=1)
    rouge_1_score = rouge_n(y_true, y_pred)
    rouge_l = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeL()
    rouge_l_score = rouge_l(y_true, y_pred)
    return rouge_1_score, rouge_2_score, rouge_l_score

Training¶

The build_model method is defined with various arguments so that hyperparameters can be injected from outside. Hereby, the same method can be used for various hyperparameter tunings.

In [ ]:
def run_training(
        model,
        train_ds,
        validation_ds,
        optimizer,
        epochs,
        steps_per_epoch,
        now,
        verbose,
        callbacks=[]):
    """
    Run training.
    :train_ds: training set
    :validation_ds: validation set
    :optimizer: optimizer.Optimizer
    :epochs: the number of epochs
    :steps_per_epoch: the number of weight updates in a epoch
    :now: timestamp
    """
    metrics = [
        masked_acc,
        #keras.metrics.SparseCategoricalAccuracy(),
        #keras_nlp.metrics.RougeN(), #  This cannot be used here
    ]
    model.compile(
        optimizer=optimizer,
        metrics=metrics,
        loss=masked_loss,
        weighted_metrics=[],
    )
    callbacks.append(get_tensorboard_callback(now=now))
    history = model.fit(
        train_ds,
        epochs=epochs,
        validation_data=validation_ds,
        steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
        callbacks=callbacks,
        verbose=verbose,
    )
    return history

class RougeEvaluator(keras.callbacks.Callback):
    """
    Callback to calculate ROUGE scores for every epoch
    """
    def __init__(
            self,
            dataset,
            max_length):
        """
        :dataset: dataset object that is used for ROUGE evaluation
        :max_length: the max length of the summarized text
        """
        self.dataset = dataset
        self.max_length = max_length
  
    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        y_true, y_pred = predict_dataset(
            model=self.model,
            iterable_dataset=tfds.as_numpy(self.dataset),
            decoder_sequence_length=self.max_length
        )
        rouge_1_score, rouge_2_score, rouge_l_score = calculate_rouge_score(
            y_true=y_true,
            y_pred=y_pred
        )
        print(rouge_1_score)
        print(rouge_2_score)
        print(rouge_l_score)

def build_model(
        train_ds, validation_ds, test_ds,
        vectorization_layer,
        num_encoders,
        num_decoders,
        num_heads,
        dropout,
        transformer_intermediate_dim,
        normalize_first,
        layer_norm_epsilon,
        encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_residual,
        vocab_size,
        batch_size,
        embedding_dim,
        mask_zero,
        optimizer,
        epochs,
        steps_per_epoch,
        verbose=1,
        callbacks=[]):
    """
    Build the model with specified parameters.
    :return: model: trained model
    :return: filepath: model file path if it is saved
    :return: history: history object to plot
    """
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    if DEBUGGER_V2:
        tf.debugging.experimental.enable_dump_debug_info(
            get_log_dir(now=now),
            tensor_debug_mode="FULL_HEALTH",
            circular_buffer_size=-1
        )
    # before validation_ds is transformed
    # if verbose > 0 and validation_ds is not None:
    #     callbacks.append(RougeEvaluator(
    #         dataset=validation_ds,
    #         max_length=decoder_sequence_length,
    #     ))
    input_vectorization_layer, target_vectorization_layer = prepare_tokenizer(
        vectorization_layer=vectorization_layer,
        encoder_sequence_length=encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
        max_tokens=vocab_size,
    )
    train_ds, validation_ds, test_ds = build_datasets(
        train_ds=train_ds,
        validation_ds=validation_ds,
        test_ds=test_ds,
        vectorization_layer=vectorization_layer,
        batch_size=batch_size,
        encoder_sequence_length=encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
    )

    input_vocab_size = input_vectorization_layer.vocabulary_size()
    target_vocab_size = target_vectorization_layer.vocabulary_size()
    model = TransformerEncoderDecoderModel(
        encoder_tokenizer=input_vectorization_layer,
        decoder_tokenizer=target_vectorization_layer,
        num_encoders=num_encoders,
        num_decoders=num_decoders,
        num_heads=num_heads,
        dropout=dropout,
        transformer_intermediate_dim=transformer_intermediate_dim,
        normalize_first=normalize_first,
        layer_norm_epsilon=layer_norm_epsilon,
        encoder_vocabulary_size=input_vocab_size,
        decoder_vocabulary_size=target_vocab_size,
        embedding_dim=embedding_dim,
        mask_zero=mask_zero,
        encoder_sequence_length=encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
        use_residual=use_residual,
    )
    # This should be called seemingly.
    model.build(
        input_shape=(
            (None, encoder_sequence_length),
            (None, decoder_sequence_length)
        )
    )

    history = run_training(
        model,
        train_ds=train_ds,
        validation_ds=validation_ds,
        optimizer=optimizer,
        epochs=epochs,
        steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
        now=now,
        verbose=verbose,
        callbacks=callbacks,
    )

    timestamp = now.strftime('%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S')
    if is_running_on_apple_silicon() or is_running_on_intel_mac():
        filepath = f'model/summarization_model_{timestamp}.keras'
    else:
        filepath = f'summarization_model_{timestamp}.keras'
    print(f"Saving to {filepath}")
    model.save(filepath=filepath)

    print(f"Successfully saved model to {filepath}")
    return model, filepath, history

Transformer Decoder-Only Model¶

To exhibit the superiority of the Transformer encoder-decoder model on text summarization tasks, another architecture, which is the Transformer decoder-only model, is defined as follows (Figure 4.5). This model that is implemented in the TransformerDecoderModel class is a simpler architecture where the encoder mechanisms are just removed. Specifically, this model has an embedding layer, 2 Transformer decoder layers, and a dense layer.

In [ ]:
@saving.register_keras_serializable()
class TransformerDecoderModel(keras.Model):
    """
    Transformer model class that contains Transformer Decoder inside.
    :param decoder_tokenizer: tf.keras.layers.TextVectorization object
    :num_decoders: the number of decoders
    :num_heads: the number of heads (Attention mechanism)
    :dropout: the dropout rate
    :transformer_intermediate_dim: the number of dimensions in each decoder
    :normalize_first: Pre-Layer Normalization or Post-Layer Normalization
    :layer_norm_epsilon: the epsilon value in layer normalization components.
    :decoder_vocabulary_size: the number of decoder vocabulary size
    :embedding_dim: the dimension for embedding
    :mask_zero: whether 0 is used the mask value
    :decoder_sequence_length: the length of decoder sequence
    :use_residual: whether residual connections are used outside of the Transformer decoder
    """
    def __init__(
        self,
        decoder_tokenizer,
        num_decoders,
        num_heads,
        dropout,
        transformer_intermediate_dim,
        normalize_first,
        layer_norm_epsilon,
        decoder_vocabulary_size,
        embedding_dim,
        mask_zero,
        decoder_sequence_length,
        use_residual,
        **kwargs):
        super(TransformerDecoderModel, self).__init__(**kwargs)
        self.mask_zero = mask_zero
        self.layer_norm_epsilon = layer_norm_epsilon
        self.use_residual = use_residual
        self.decoders = []
        if isinstance(layer_norm_epsilon, list):
            decoder_layer_norm_epsilons = layer_norm_epsilon
        else:
            decoder_layer_norm_epsilons = [layer_norm_epsilon for _ in range(num_decoders)]

        for i in range(num_decoders):
            self.decoders.append(
                keras_nlp.layers.TransformerDecoder(
                    num_heads=num_heads,
                    dropout=dropout,
                    intermediate_dim=transformer_intermediate_dim,
                    normalize_first=normalize_first,
                    layer_norm_epsilon=decoder_layer_norm_epsilons[i],
                    name=f"decoder_{i}",
                )
            )

        self.decoder_tokenizer = decoder_tokenizer

        self.decoder_embedding = keras_nlp.layers.TokenAndPositionEmbedding(
            vocabulary_size=decoder_vocabulary_size,
            sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
            embedding_dim=embedding_dim,
            mask_zero=mask_zero,
            name="decoder_embed",
        )

        self.dense = keras.layers.Dense(
            decoder_vocabulary_size,
            name="dense",
        )

    def call(self, inputs, training=False):
        """
        This method defines and represents the calculation graph (tensor flow).
        :training: True, when calculating val_loss and val_acc. Otherwise, False.
        """
        decoder_input = inputs[0]
        decoded = self.decoder_embedding(decoder_input)
        for decoder in self.decoders:
            if self.use_residual and len(self.decoders) > 1:
                residual = decoded
            decoded = decoder(
                decoder_sequence=decoded,
                #encoder_sequence=encoded,
                use_causal_mask=True,
                training=training,
            )
            if self.use_residual and len(self.decoders) > 1:
                decoded = decoded + residual

        output = self.dense(decoded)
        try:
            # Drop the keras mask, so it doesn't scale the losses/metrics.
            # b/250038731
            del output._keras_mask
        except AttributeError:
            pass
        return output

    def get_config(self):
        """
        This method is used to save a model into a file.
        """
        config = super(TransformerDecoderModel, self).get_config().copy()
        config.update({
            "decoder_tokenizer": self.decoder_tokenizer.get_config(),
            "num_decoders": len(self.decoders),
            "num_heads": self.decoders[0].num_heads,
            "dropout" : self.decoders[0].dropout,
            "transformer_intermediate_dim": self.decoders[0].intermediate_dim,
            "normalize_first": self.decoders[0].normalize_first,
            "layer_norm_epsilon": self.layer_norm_epsilon,
            "decoder_vocabulary_size": self.decoder_embedding.vocabulary_size,
            "embedding_dim": self.decoder_embedding.embedding_dim,
            "mask_zero": self.mask_zero,
            "decoder_sequence_length": self.decoder_embedding.sequence_length,
            "use_residual": self.use_residual,
        })
        return config
    @classmethod
    def from_config(cls, config):
        """
        This method is used to build a model from a saved file.
        """
        decoder_tokenizer_config = config.pop("decoder_tokenizer")
        decoder_tokenizer = keras.layers.TextVectorization.from_config(decoder_tokenizer_config)
        return cls(
            decoder_tokenizer=decoder_tokenizer,
            **config
        )

BART Model¶

Since the basic Transformer encoder-decoder model has reached the performance limitation, the pre-trained BART model is used for the summarization task. Specifically, the model has 6 to 12 Transformer encoders and decoders, connected as the following diagram represents the architecture (Figure 4.6). It is the same as the basic Transformer model aside from the pre-training with the tasks mentioned in the Literature Review section.

Prediction¶

Like the prediction of the basic Transformer encoder-decoder model, the model derives a word to make a sequence. However, the implementation is hidden, and it is possible to generate a summarized sentence just by using the generate method.

In [ ]:
def generate_text(
        model,
        input_text,
        max_length=64):
    """
    Generate summarized text
    :model: the trained BART model
    :input_text: the original text that is summarized
    :max_length: the length of the summarized text
    """
    output = model.generate(
        input_text,
        max_length=max_length
    )
    return output

def generate_prediction_result(
        bart_lm,
        ds,
        max_length=64):
    """
    Generate summarized text from the dataset
    :bart_lm: the trained BART model
    :ds: the dataset, which is mainly text set, that is summarized
    :max_length: the length of the summarized text
    """
    x = []
    y_true = []
    for row in ds:
        x.append(row["encoder_text"].numpy())
        y_true.append(row["decoder_text"].numpy())

    # The first call to XLA generally takes a bit longer
    # because the XLA contains overhead of compilation and optimization.
    _ = generate_text(
        bart_lm,
        "dummy",
        max_length=max_length
    )

    y_pred = generate_text(
        bart_lm,
        ds.map(lambda row: row["encoder_text"]).batch(8),
        max_length=max_length,
    )
    return x, y_true, y_pred

def calculate_rouge_score(y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Calculate the ROUGE scores
    :y_true: the ground truth value
    :y_pred: the generated summarized text
    :returns: ROUGE-1 score
    :returns: ROUGE-2 score
    :returns: ROUGE-L score
    """
    rouge_n = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeN(order=2)
    rouge_2_score = rouge_n(y_true, y_pred)
    rouge_n = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeN(order=1)
    rouge_1_score = rouge_n(y_true, y_pred)
    rouge_l = keras_nlp.metrics.RougeL()
    rouge_l_score = rouge_l(y_true, y_pred)
    return rouge_1_score, rouge_2_score, rouge_l_score

Training¶

The build_bart_model method is defined with various arguments so that hyperparameters can be injected from outside. Hereby, the same method can be used for various hyperparameter tunings.

In [ ]:
class RougeEvaluator(keras.callbacks.Callback):
    """
    Callback to calculate ROUGE scores for every epoch
    """
    def __init__(
            self,
            dataset,
            max_length):
        """
        :dataset: dataset object that is used for ROUGE evaluation
        :max_length: the max length of the summarized text
        """
        self.dataset = dataset
        self.max_length = max_length
  
    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        _, y_true, y_pred = generate_prediction_result(
            bart_lm=self.model,
            ds=self.dataset,
            max_length=self.max_length
        )
        rouge_1_score, rouge_2_score, rouge_l_score = calculate_rouge_score(
            y_true=y_true,
            y_pred=y_pred
        )
        print(rouge_1_score)
        print(rouge_2_score)
        print(rouge_l_score)

def format_dataset_bart_seq2seq(row):
    """
    BART pre-trained model assumes that
    the encoder and decoder text key are "encoder_text" and "decoder_text", respectively.
    """
    return {
        "encoder_text": row["dialogue"],
        "decoder_text": row["summary"]
    }
    
def build_bart_model(
    training_data,
    validation_data,
    encoder_sequence_length=128,  # 128: 75% covered. max is 803.
    decoder_sequence_length=64,  # 32: 75% covered. max is 64
    learning_rate=5e-5,
    weight_decay=0.01,
    epsilon=1e-6,
    global_clipnorm=1.0,
    batch_size=8,
    epochs=5,
    preset_name="bart_base_en",
    verbose=1,
    is_saved=False):
    """
    Build the BART model with specified parameters.
    :return: model: trained BART model
    :return: filepath: model file path if it is saved
    :return: history: history object to plot
    """
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    preprocessor = keras_nlp.models.BartSeq2SeqLMPreprocessor.from_preset(
        preset_name,
        encoder_sequence_length=encoder_sequence_length,
        decoder_sequence_length=decoder_sequence_length,
    )
    bart_lm = keras_nlp.models.BartSeq2SeqLM.from_preset(
        preset_name,
        preprocessor=preprocessor
    )
    callbacks = []
    # if verbose > 0:
    #     bart_lm.summary()
    #     if validation_data is not None and not is_running_on_apple_silicon():
    #         callbacks.append(RougeEvaluator(
    #             dataset=validation_data.map(format_dataset_bart_seq2seq),
    #             max_length=decoder_sequence_length,
    #         ))

    optimizer = keras.optimizers.AdamW(
        learning_rate=learning_rate,
        weight_decay=weight_decay,
        epsilon=epsilon,
        global_clipnorm=global_clipnorm,
    )

    # Exclude layernorm terms and bias terms from weight decay.
    optimizer.exclude_from_weight_decay(var_names=[
        "bias",
        "gamma",
        "beta",
    ])

    bart_lm.compile(
        optimizer=optimizer,
        loss=keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
        weighted_metrics=[
            "accuracy"
        ],
    )
    val_ds = None
    if validation_data is not None:
        val_ds = validation_data.map(format_dataset_bart_seq2seq).batch(batch_size).cache()
    callbacks.append(get_tensorboard_callback(now=now))
    history = bart_lm.fit(
        training_data.map(format_dataset_bart_seq2seq).batch(batch_size).cache(),
        validation_data=val_ds,
        epochs=epochs,
        verbose=verbose,
        callbacks=callbacks,
    )

    filepath = None
    if is_saved:
        timestamp = now.strftime('%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S')
        if is_running_on_apple_silicon() or is_running_on_intel_mac():
            filepath = f'model/summarization_bart_model_{timestamp}.keras'
        else:
            filepath = f'summarization_bart_model_{timestamp}.keras'
        print(f"Saving to {filepath}")
        bart_lm.save(filepath=filepath)
        print(f"Successfully saved model to {filepath}")

    return bart_lm, filepath, history

Build¶

The best model is built with the hyperparameter set, which is derived by the experiments.

Evaluation¶

Performance Difference¶

Model Loss Accuracy ROUGE-1 ROUGE-2 ROUGE-L
Base 1.763 0.248 8.3 0.8 7.9
Transformer decoder-only model 6.264 0.100 14.5 0.7 11.9
Transformer encoder-decoder model 1.778 0.274 26.7 6.9 21.6
BART 0.691 0.594 44.1 18.5 35.1

The BART model has drastically overcome other models. Additionally, for human readers, the quality difference of summarized text on each model is larger than the metrics difference.

Here, the reasons why the basic Transformer encoder-decoder model did not improve performance even though its architecture is similar to the BART model and it is experimented to have more heads, layers, units, and so on will be analyzed. The differences between the Transformer encoder-decoder model and the pre-trained BART model are visually recognizable as follows;

Transformer Encoder-Decoder Model

BART Model

These are visualized weight scores of the first encoder layers in the basic Transformer encoder-decoder and the BART models. The former (Figure 5.1) well-represents the relationship between the word "car" in the first sentence and the word "buy" in the second sentence. However, all 6 attention heads resemble the others. That indicates 6 attentions captured similar features, even though they are expected to capture different features from text. Whereas all attentions in the BART model, which is represented in the latter one (Figure 5.2), have 12 significantly different and distinctive attentions. That is, in the BART model, the attention layers were able to capture various kinds of features. Most of them are caused by the pre-training phase. As a result, that made a difference in the amount of features and, finally, in the performance. That is one of the exciting and impressive points in the report.

Hypothesis Verification¶

Hyperparameter tunings are significantly effective even on a Transformer model.

This is partially true. The number of epochs, such as classification and regression models, is still significant. The training must be stopped at the best epoch number to avoid overfitting. Otherwise, the model overfits the training data.

Moreover, the learning rate makes a remarkable difference in the training curve. When the learning rate 1e-3, the same as the tuned basic Transformer encoder-decoder model, is used for fine-tuning the BART model, this phase does not improve the performance. It should be started with less than 1e-5. That is, there must be an appropriate learning rate for each learning progress. Changing the learning rate on the way to training might improve performance a bit.

However, the most of other hyperparameters did not affect the performance unexpectedly and significantly.

Pre-trained models improve the text summarization performance.

The BART model was built for this text summarization model. It was able to improve performance significantly more than expected. As a result, it was found that knowledge of language is more effective than hyperparameter tuning. The basic Transformer encoder-decoder model did not improve the performance even if it had more encoders and more decoders. The knowledge, which was obtained with pre-training, reduced the loss by 0.6 and increases the accuracy, the ROUGE-1 metric, the ROUGE-2 metric, and the ROUGE-L metric, by 148%, 65%, 168%, and 63%, respectively.

Transformer models can generate text more sophisticatedly than dense layer models.

It did not turn out how to build a dense layer model that is comparable with the Transformer model for text summarization tasks.

Instead, an RNN sequence-to-sequence model, which was more practical, was used to build a text summarization model as the base model. This hypothesis was partially shown to be correct, comparing the basic Transformer encoder-decoder model with the basic RNN model. The basic Transformer model was easily able to achieve a higher score. Note that the RNN model in this experiment is just for benchmarks, and it has not been well-tuned compared to the Transformer model. It is not always that the RNN model should not be used.

The encoder-decoder model of the Transformer works better for text summarization tasks than the only-decoder model.

This is partially true. In the case where their network is almost the same size without any pre-trained models, the encoder-decoder model is advantageous to the decoder-only models because the encoder-decoder model can use the whole original text from the encoder and all previous words from the decoder to predict the next word.

Moreover, the decoder-only models have a drawback where the input sequence length is the same as the output sequence length. It seems slightly inappropriate since the summarized text is mostly shorter than the input text.

The GPT model is one of the decoder-only architectures. Even though it might be possible to improve the performance in the case that the pre-trained model is used for this task, the experiment has not intentionally been executed so as not to deviate from the purpose of simply comparing with the Transformer encoder-decoder model.

Optional investigation of RetNet

It has not been executed due to the following reasons.

  • Even though the comparative experiment with the Transformer model requires the highly optimized implementation, the stable implementation is only in PyTorch [30] and it is difficult to fairly compare the TensorFlow/Keras implementation.
  • It is distant from the domain user's objective, which is the text summarization task. (It was more strongly focused on the personal interest.)

This was one of the shortcomings of this research plan. Therefore, it was deprioritized, and finally, the time was instead used to present the superiority of the Transformer model, compared to other models.

Hyperparameters¶

Most of the best parameters have been identified experimentally. Not all combinations of hyperparameters are tested, but it is almost impossible to examine all combinations of hyperparameters. For example, no one knows whether there is a better value between empirically picked values on a numeric parameter than them. We rely on the assumption that it is supposed that it must be the best model after repeatedly choosing the better hyperparameters. And this is empirically true. Here are the hyperparameters that were identified in this report:

  • The number of Transformer encoders
  • The number of Transformer decoders
  • The number of attention heads
  • The dropout rate
  • The dimensions of the Transformer intermediate layer
  • Whether the normalization layer puts on a forward or backward
  • The epsilon for normalization of the Transformer
  • Whether the external residual connection is used
  • The batch size
  • The dimensions of the embedding
  • The number of epochs

Sequence length between the encoder and the decoder¶

The decoder sequence length was not compared because the loss value directly gets worse if the length is shorter the maximum length of the summarized text of the dataset. That does not reflect the model performance. And although the encoder sequence length can be shortened to reduce memory consumption, we must be careful because it loses the features from the dataset text.

Model Size¶

Model Trainable params Optimizer params File Size
Transformer encoder-decoder 14,118,407 (53.86 MB) - 284 MB
BART (bart_large_en_cnn) 406,286,336 (1.51 GB) 812,572,678 (3.03 GB) 8.13 GB
BART (bart_base_en) 139,417,344 (531.83 MB) 278,834,694 (1.04 GB) 2.79 GB

The same amount as each parameter size consumes the memory on the device. In the case where the summarization model runs on a server, any models above can run smoothly. Therefore, if there is not the restriction, the large BART model should be chosen due to its performance. If the other programs consume the memory, it might be better for the smaller BART model to run on the server. Finally, the Transformer encoder-decoder model should be chosen if the model runs on any mobile device. Only some high-end devices can currently run the 2.79 GB BART model.

Note that the greater the number of parameters, the more time it takes to load. In the case the prediction process is launched every time, larger models take longer time to launch and get ready for the prediction.

The training of the Transformer encoder-decoder model was 2.6 times faster than the base RNN model, even though the base model had fewer layers and no attention mechanisms. That proved Transformer architecture is prior in the aspect of training parallelization.

The training of the BART model took 8 times longer time. It must be considered especially in the case where the code runs on a paid-per-hours environment such as AWS SageMaker. If the model requires many hyperparameter tunings, that will be a point of concern. If the BART model required many executions of the training phase, that would have been one of the obstacles.

Prediction Time¶

Model NVIDIA V100 GPU Apple Silicon M2
Transformer encoder-decoder ※2459s ※599s
BART 241s -

※ Note that this is not a fair comparison for the following reasons.

Unexpectedly, the BART model could run faster than the Transformer encoder-decoder model, which has fewer parameters. The BART model internally uses the BERT tokenizer, which inherits the WordPieceTokenizer class, and has the detokenize method that can detokenize with the RaggedTensor natively. In contrast, the Transformer model detokenizes every word one by one with a Python loop, non-natively. Because the TextVectorization layer of the TensorFlow library does not have the detokenization method, there is no way to compare them fairly.

Additionally, it is possible to use the batch on the BART model detokenization. When a batch size 8 was used, the same text could be processed for 34 seconds. That is more than 8 times faster.

The time values are for 819 dialogues from the text dataset. It is hard to process the prediction in parallel due to computational resource bottleneck (not I/O bottleneck). So, if the Transformer encoder-decoder model is run on the actual environment, it must be well-tuned like the BART model.

Conclusion¶

Up to here, I have researched text summarization tasks and derived the best model practically and experimentally.

Even though the base RNN model might be improved with attention mechanisms, there is still the problem of a training time of more than 2.6 times longer. Moreover, the RNN model consumed RAM 4 times more than the Transformer encoder-decoder model in the local environment. Those were the advantages of the Transformer model shown in this project.

The first basic Transformer encoder-decoder model was trained only with the dataset that I have downloaded. Even though the various hyperparameter tunings were executed for this model, the loss value only got slightly smaller, and the accuracy value only got slightly larger. The BART model, which was pre-trained with corpora, such as BooksCorpus, English Wikipedia, and CommonCrawl [28], was fine-tuned with the dataset I downloaded. This BART model easily overwhelmed the first basic Transformer model.

That indicates the effectiveness and necessity of the pre-training, which is based on transfer learning. In other words, the model with the fundamental comprehension for the whole language, English in this case, is effective for the text summarization task. Meanwhile, the model without language comprehension is easily overfitted because the dataset is everything for the model, and the model does not have linguistic knowledge at all. As a result, it was problematic from the aspect of the generalization performance.

Future Research¶

This time, only the greedy search algorithm, where the most probable tokens were selected to construct, was used to decode a prediction result into a sentence. The comparison of the decoding methods was not executed. For example, if the beam search algorithm, where some of the more probable sequences at each time step are internally held and the best next token is predicted from them, was used, there would have been room to improve the quality of the predicted sequences.

Additionally, if the implementation supported the visualization of all other MultiHeadAttention layers in a Transformer model, the MultiHeadAttention of the first TransformerDecoder could have represented which words in a dialog correspond to words in the summary. That would be the beneficial information for the report.

Moreover, as shown in the visualization of the MultiHeadAttention of the BART model, the word tokenization, simply provided by the TextVectorization class, is not used. Instead, the BERT tokenizer, one of the subword segmentation/tokenization, is used in the BART model. Therefore, there are differences not only in the pre-trained but also in preprocessing and postprocessing between the Transformer encoder-decoder and BART models. Though there is no doubt of the power of pre-training, there is still room to execute the comparison in the same preconditions.

Finally, the ROUGE score was used to measure the summarized text quality in this report. However, they are n-gram-based metrics, and it is not always that the text that marked a higher ROUGE score corresponds to the text human readers recognize better summarization, though the metrics and the feeling are correlated. There might be a better unknown way.

Reflecting on the Development Process¶

It took a lot of time to identify the following problems in the development process:

  1. The loss value is higher, and the accuracy value is lower than expected.
  2. The training speed is slower than expected.

The limitation of a model is known only empirically. That is, when we face a lower performance than expected, it is difficult to logically identify whether the reason is the limitation of the model architecture or unknown bugs that cause the lower performance. As a result, code reviews were repeated with the suspicion that there should be bugs causing the low performance. In this time-consuming process, some minor bugs were fixed. For example, one of the bugs caused the transformations of tensors to be wrong, where the end Out Of Vocabulary (OOV) tags were added incorrectly. However, they were not so impactful to its performance. The TensorBoard tool was used to visualize the model graph to find unknown bugs. Eventually, that was just the limitation of the model architecture.

Moreover, the speed where the training and predicting runs is also known only empirically.

_ NVIDIA V100 GPU x 1 Mac Apple Silicon M2 Mac Intel
1 step time 3~10 times faster 1 10 times slower
RAM 16 GB GPU memory 32 GB 32 GB
tensorflow-text/BART o partially works o

The M2 Mac machine was mainly used as the development machine. The tensorflow-metal was used to accelerate it. However, the NVIDIA V100 GPU environment is at least 3 to 10 times faster. Especially when the RAM of the Mac is not enough for calculations, that makes a lot of swaps and at least 3 times slower than usual. The old Intel Mac was 10 times slower than the M2 Mac and useless, as shown in the above table.

Whereas, when the tensor data overflowed from the NVIDIA V100 16GB GPU memory, the training program was killed by the Out-Of-Memory error (OOM). That is, it must calculate only within 16GB. Due to this restriction, the dataset was changed from the CNN dailymail dataset to the SAMSum dataset.

In this research, the KerasNLP library was used, and some classes were dependent on the tensorflow-text library. When the research started, the tensorflow-text library did not support Apple Silicon Mac, and the situation did not change until July 2024. Even though it started supporting, the BART model does not work yet.

Ethical Consideration¶

In the experiments of this research, critical problems with the dataset biases did not emerge. However, all datasets contain biases, which might be problematic. For example, the paper "The Unequal Opportunities of Large Language Models: Revealing Demographic Bias through Job Recommendations" [27] reveals the inequality of Large Language Models (LLM) on job recommendations as follows:

We demonstrate the mere mention of nationality or gender identity can significantly skew results, and developers should be hyper-aware of introducing biases into the system. If demographic attributes are necessary, developers should critically evaluate how to incorporate this information fairly and conduct experiments to understand and address biases. [27]

Just in terms of the controllability of the models, the basic Transformer encoder-decoder model holds the advantage over the pre-trained BART model because the problematic entries can be excluded from the training dataset or be weakened from the perspective of the whole model. Therefore, the best practice will be for the BART model to run and for the basic Transformer model to be prepared as a backup plan for a problematic situation.
